<spring_boot_security_guide>
<title>SPRING BOOT SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Spring Boot applications have framework-specific vulnerabilities including actuator endpoint exposure, SpEL injection, Spring4Shell patterns, bean manipulation, property injection, and Thymeleaf SSTI. Focus on misconfigured actuators, expression language injection, and deserialization issues.</critical>

<scope>
- Actuator endpoint exposure and exploitation
- SpEL (Spring Expression Language) injection
- Spring4Shell (CVE-2022-22965) patterns
- Bean manipulation and injection
- Property injection (@Value vulnerabilities)
- Thymeleaf Server-Side Template Injection (SSTI)
- Spring Security bypass techniques
- Deserialization vulnerabilities
- Path traversal in static resources
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify Spring Boot version and dependencies
2. Enumerate actuator endpoints
3. Test SpEL injection in all input vectors
4. Check for Spring4Shell vulnerability patterns
5. Probe @RequestParam and @Value for injection
6. Test Thymeleaf templates for SSTI
7. Analyze Spring Security configuration
8. Test deserialization in sessions and caching
</methodology>

